<NotesLayout
  title="Investing — principles I keep returning to"
  description="The durable ideas: diversification, cost, risk, and time horizon — minus the noise."
  tag="Investments"
  updated="28 Jun 2026"
>
  <p>
    The hard part of investing isn't picking winners — it's behaviour. These are
    the few ideas that have survived contact with reality for me.
  </p>

  <h2>The durable principles</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Time in the market beats timing the market.</strong> Missing a handful of the best days wrecks long-run returns.</li>
    <li><strong>Cost is the one variable I control.</strong> A 1% fee compounds against me as surely as returns compound for me.</li>
    <li><strong>Diversify</strong> across assets and geographies — it lowers risk without an equivalent cut to expected return.</li>
    <li><strong>Match risk to time horizon.</strong> Money I need within a few years shouldn't ride the equity rollercoaster.</li>
    <li><strong>Rebalance on a schedule, not on emotion.</strong> It mechanically sells high and buys low.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Risk vs time horizon (rough guide)</h2>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Horizon</th><th>Tolerance for swings</th><th>Tilt</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>&lt; 3 years</td><td>Low</td><td>Cash / short bonds</td></tr>
      <tr><td>3–10 years</td><td>Medium</td><td>Balanced mix</td></tr>
      <tr><td>10+ years</td><td>Higher</td><td>Equity-heavy</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>Behaviour traps to watch for</h2>
  <blockquote>
    Chasing last year's winner · Panic-selling in a drawdown · Confusing a good
    company with a good investment (price already reflects the story) · Tinkering
    too often and paying for it in costs and tax.
  </blockquote>

  <h2>My checklist before any move</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>What's the time horizon for this money?</li>
    <li>What does it cost — all in, including platform and fund fees?</li>
    <li>Is this diversified, or a concentrated bet I'm telling myself is diversified?</li>
    <li>Which wrapper (pension / ISA / general) should hold it? (See the tax note.)</li>
    <li>Would I be comfortable if it fell 30% next year?</li>
  </ol>

  <hr />
  <p><strong>One-liner:</strong> low cost, broadly diversified, held for a long time, left alone.</p>
</NotesLayout>
